<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-150-454  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 150 454.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  Feb 8 1990 v35 n3A p53(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sharp negotiating can win you a heftier raise. (consider how workaffect profits and what experience is worth)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ward, Mark L. Sr.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The ability to prove one's worth is an ideal strategy whennegotiating a pay raise.andP;  The employee should first make anappointment with the boss to discuss the salary increase.andO;Employees should then use the time before the meeting to plan astrategy.andP;  One author says employees next step is to create apositive atmosphere and do 'homework' to assure the boss that theyhave an interest in the company.andP;  Roger Dawson, another author,suggests starting the meeting with a positive statement thatsuggests the salary increase will be affordable.andP;  Dawson alsosuggests 'bracketing,' or asking for an increase that is an equaldistance from current salary and the actual desired salary.andP;  Ifthe boss says that the company can not afford salary increases,the employee should be prepared to offer figures on significantcontributions that increased profits or productivity.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SalaryNegotiationPersonnel.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>